  "why": "The paper evaluates its method, BET, in two distinct scenarios: Single Model Testing (ST) and Differential Testing (DT). In the ST scenario, the evaluation is strictly limited to the single model under test; the paper does not attempt to apply the discovered error-inducing inputs to other models to check for failure transferability. In the DT scenario, the goal is to find inputs that cause behavioral disagreements between a model and its quantized version (e.g., C(x) ≠ C_quantized(x)). The metric's coding guidance explicitly states that \"Multi-model disagreement used as a differential oracle during fuzzing is not cross-model transferability.\" The paper's methodology and evaluation for DT fall directly into this excluded category. Consequently, the paper does not demonstrate or evaluate whether the failures it discovers can transfer across different models.",
  "evidence": "Page 4, Section beginning 'There are two common scenarios...': \"There are two common scenarios for CNN testing, i.e., differential testing (DT) [31, 46] and single model testing (ST) [12, 19]. DT finds error-inducing inputs which trigger behavior inconsistencies among multiple models that have similar functionality (e.g., models of self-driving cars by Google and Tesla) and can work without labeled data. For example, given two CNN models C1, C2 with similar functionality, an error-inducing input xerr is found if C1(xerr) ≠ C2(xerr). ST only focuses on one target model C to find error-inducing inputs and requires labels for test data.\"\n\nPage 8, Section 4.2, 'Evaluation of Black-Box Differential Testing': \"Baselines. We compare BET with the highly-related black-box testing method DiffChaser [46]... Constructing differential models. To get a convincing DT result, we directly use Tensorflow-Lite... to construct quantized models for DT as DiffChaser does... cause disagreements between the original model with its quantized models. e.g., generating error-inducing inputs between ResNet50 with ResNet50-q8.\"\n\nPage 10, Section 4.3, 'BET for Single Model Testing': This section presents results for ST. The tables (Table 5, 6, 7, 8) evaluate each model (e.g., VGG16, ResNet18) independently, with no experiments showing that errors found for one model are tested against another."
